tap water aside from fresh mountain stream water and good-quality bottled spring water, filtered tap water is generally the best option for brewing tea.it should have a total dissolved solids (tds) content of 30 parts per million (ppm) or less.if you’re deciding between spring water and good, filtered tap water, you may also want to consider the cost and environmental impact of using bottled water.quality spring water is the optimal bottled water for tea, but some types are better than others.well water poses a special problem for tea brewing because its ph is almost always above 7.i use a regular brita filter, but there are more sophisticated water filters on the market for those with specific water problems or a desire for truly excellent water.distilled water is too soft (low in minerals) and will brew into flat-tasting tea.freshly drawn filtered water is the best option for most tea brewers.some neutral-tasting tap water may not even need to be filtered.as soft water produces flat-tasting tea, some serious tea aficionados warm soft water with certain types of rocks in the kettle.the best spring water for tea should be neutral in ph (about 7) and in flavor.in ancient times, the tea scholar lu yu said the best water for brewing tea came from the center of a swiftly moving mountain stream.mineral water is toohard (mineral-rich) and may leave your tea tasting metallic or harsh.(water absorbs odors over time and, if your water has been sitting out in your kitchen for a while, you tea’s flavor may be negatively impacted.)this adds a better balance of minerals to the water and the final brew.